{
  "doc_id": "13111",
  "text": "Impaired JA is a primary, characteristic feature of Autism Spectrum Disorder (ASD) [CITATION_1] , which may contribute to differences in language development and social behavior in individuals with ASD [CITATION_2] . Children with ASD often also demonstrate lowered ToM capabilities [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Understanding better the continuities or discontinuities for the typical relationship between JA and ToM might, therefore, inform the refinement of effective joint attention-based interventions for individuals with ASD [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . Therefore, with this study, we aimed to (1) test the widely held assumption that ToM and JA naturally or normally cooccur, working with a sample of neurotypical adult humans who could give subjective reports of their thoughts, and (2) to establish methods that could, in the future, be adapted to test aspects of the third major aforementioned hypothesis in typically and atypically developing children. By directly testing for the association between operationally-defined occurrences of ToM and JA, we were able to measure the relative frequencies of mental state attributions during JA as compared to non-JA behaviors and, consequently, begin to answer the question of whether thinking about another adult's mental states is necessary for participation in JA.",
